of ethnic violence in Kenya, the authors analyse how local patterns of conflict among pastoralists were influenced by both national and regional politics, which have encouraged an increased tendency of territorialized ethnicity. The authors then discuss ways of getting out of the ethnic trap and revitalizing a mobile livestock economy in a region where other forms of land use are impossible or much less effective. A companion volume to Islam and Ethnicity in Northern Kenya and Southern Ethiopia, it will be of particular interest to political anthropologists, students of nomadism, pastoral economy ecology, and globalization. Günther Schlee is director of the Department of 'Integration and Conflict', Max Planck Institute forSocial Anthropology, Halle, Germany; Abdullahi Shongolo is an independent scholar based in Kenya.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnic conflictzEthiopia. 0aEthnic conflictzKenya. 0aPastoral systemszEthiopia. 0aPastoral systemszKenya. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / African.2bisacsh  aAnthropological research.  aConflict.  aDevelopment.  aEthnic Violence.  aEthnic territories.  aGlobalization.  aLivestock economy.  aNomadism.  aNorthern Kenya.  aPastoralism.  aPastoralists.  aPolicies.  aPolitics.  aReversing trends.  aSouthern Ethiopia.  aTerritorialized ethnicity.1 aSchlee, Günther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShongolo, Abdullahi A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aShongolo, Abdullahi A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204214340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/